1
00:00:01,702 --> 00:00:30,207
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:31,992 --> 00:00:41,142
So the reason I'm taping it is because I'd like to know what I have to say for myself.

3
00:00:43,045 --> 00:01:02,393
because I haven't given this sort of talk before, specifically anyway, and Jim has asked me to do a little sort of biography and to sort of talk about the Buddhist perspective on some of Jesus Christ's teachings.

4
00:01:03,674 --> 00:01:12,427
So just so that you're sure I'm not coming in from a completely blank space, I was brought up as a Roman Catholic,

5
00:01:12,408 --> 00:01:16,933
And my mother was an Italian and my father was English.

6
00:01:18,274 --> 00:01:24,519
They met as he came up from Africa in the RAF and was billeted on her building, on her home.

7
00:01:25,361 --> 00:01:28,103
He fell immediately in love, but I think she took a bit more time.

8
00:01:30,725 --> 00:01:36,591
And on his side, going back to his grandfather, his grandfather was on his maternal side.

9
00:01:37,013 --> 00:01:42,177
His grandfather came from Milan and his wife was Irish.

10
00:01:42,579 --> 00:01:47,209
So here I am, an Italian Irish Catholic.

11
00:01:47,510 --> 00:01:49,614
You can't get more Catholic than that.

12
00:01:51,757 --> 00:02:03,340
So my experience of Catholicism is very different from some experiences that I've heard from people of my generation.

13
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:11,871
mainly because of my mother, the whole center of my Christian practice was the love of Jesus.

14
00:02:12,532 --> 00:02:22,563
I mean, I knew full well that if I missed church on Sunday and unfortunately died before I could get to confession, I would definitely end an eternity in hell.

15
00:02:23,125 --> 00:02:25,948
But that was never particularly stressed.

16
00:02:26,449 --> 00:02:27,971
It was always the love of Jesus.

17
00:02:28,651 --> 00:02:33,056
So I was very devotional as a young boy.

18
00:02:33,037 --> 00:02:38,084
And I must have been a very rare young boy that I actually enjoyed going to Mass.

19
00:02:39,366 --> 00:02:47,979
And this manifested later, around about the age of 11 and 12, of suddenly having a vocation to become a missionary priest.

20
00:02:48,719 --> 00:03:00,377
And I joined a junior seminary, which was run by the Society of the Divine Word, near Birmingham, and I spent four years in a seminary, junior seminary.

21
00:03:01,284 --> 00:03:08,551
And when I think of the regime and the training I had there, I can't imagine any modern kid even coming near it.

22
00:03:09,192 --> 00:03:22,243
I mean, we were up at 6 o'clock in the morning, we were out there in the cold doing exercises, we were back in for mass, then we had breakfast, and then we had clean-up for an hour, and then we started school.

23
00:03:22,824 --> 00:03:31,292
And then after school, there was another religious gathering, and then we had one hour off for games.

24
00:03:31,271 --> 00:03:32,152
That was it.

25
00:03:32,753 --> 00:03:34,116
And the rest of the day was in silence.

26
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:42,847
And interestingly enough, I look back upon the first two years as the halcyon days of my life.

27
00:03:43,889 --> 00:03:45,972
I was extraordinarily happy.

28
00:03:45,991 --> 00:03:48,194
I was in a continuous state of ecstasy.

29
00:03:48,655 --> 00:03:50,798
Then unfortunately, puberty entered.

30
00:03:53,622 --> 00:03:58,207
If I could have stayed as a 13-year-old, I'd have been happy for the rest of my life.

31
00:04:00,162 --> 00:04:08,603
Then something, I don't, you know, the practice was, shall we say, and this is where...

32
00:04:09,292 --> 00:04:20,168
the reason why I wanted to start with Vipassana meditation, the practice was really much to do with what we would call Samatha, which is the development of the beautiful mind.

33
00:04:20,208 --> 00:04:27,980
And it's done through imageries, through repetitive prayer, where you can lift the heart into a lovely ecstasy.

34
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:32,666
And if you think of very empowered business people,

35
00:04:32,646 --> 00:04:40,696
how they lift themselves up to this tremendous energy, and from the moment they wake up to the moment they fall asleep, they're right there on that plane of existence.

36
00:04:41,016 --> 00:04:45,682
They never drop, they just keep going, going, going, and it's always up, up, up, and get, get, get.

37
00:04:47,202 --> 00:04:53,569
And that's what happens when you can train yourself to lift your heart into a beautiful ecstasy.

38
00:04:53,630 --> 00:04:55,853
It will remain with you all day.

39
00:04:55,833 --> 00:05:04,213
And even if people say something rude to you, it doesn't affect you, it just comes off you like water on the duck's back.

40
00:05:04,233 --> 00:05:10,449
Nothing can touch you because the heart itself is lifted into this lovely state of ecstasy.

41
00:05:11,846 --> 00:05:24,959
Now, as I say, once that had passed, and then I left, and I went to school, to the sixth form in school and stuff like that, and then went to college.

42
00:05:25,819 --> 00:05:31,865
And then something which, as always, slightly amazed me, something quite peculiar happened.

43
00:05:32,425 --> 00:05:37,329
I was lying in bed on a Sunday morning, and I said to myself, I wonder what will happen if I don't go to church.

44
00:05:37,829 --> 00:05:41,853
So remember, this is hellfire we're talking about now.

45
00:05:41,834 --> 00:06:11,622
and nothing happened by the end of Sunday nothing had happened and I never went again just like that having been having been consistent with all my practice I lay in bed and said what will happen if I don't go to church nothing happened so I never went again which has been there is no you know people people talk about guilt especially in Catholicism you know and Holy Mother Church and how could you leave no guilt no sorrow no nothing it just cut like that

46
00:06:13,963 --> 00:06:19,855
And I spent the next 10 years looking like a hippie, but actually I was an existentialist.

47
00:06:20,978 --> 00:06:29,915
I didn't know what it meant, but it felt good to be an existentialist.

48
00:06:29,935 --> 00:06:33,322
I thought, well, I wasn't a nothing, I was an existentialist.

49
00:06:34,399 --> 00:06:39,338
I just felt it was so much better than being a socialist.

50
00:06:39,517 --> 00:06:44,697
It launched me into hours of discussion and talk.

51
00:06:45,875 --> 00:06:55,629
So now, then, you know, as life has it, it comes with its tribulations, and having hit a very low point, I then sought some help.

52
00:06:56,050 --> 00:06:59,053
And at the time, there was Zen Buddhism in the air.

53
00:06:59,814 --> 00:07:02,358
This was back in the 70s, middle, late 70s.

54
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:13,214
And so I wrote to the Buddhist Society, and eventually, through this and that, I ended up going to a Zen Buddhist meeting, which was held not very far from where I was living, in Birmingham.

55
00:07:13,464 --> 00:07:20,857
And I remember Vajra, whom I look upon as my spiritual mother, inviting me in.

56
00:07:21,297 --> 00:07:23,139
And her instructions were very simple.

57
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:25,283
In Zen you sit facing the wall.

58
00:07:25,863 --> 00:07:27,507
Because Bodhidharma, that's what I'm called.

59
00:07:27,968 --> 00:07:29,269
I'm called out of this particular...

60
00:07:30,350 --> 00:07:31,372
I'll come to that in a bit.

61
00:07:31,353 --> 00:07:39,060
and sit facing the wall and she said, just sit here and just watch whatever arises, whatever comes up.

62
00:07:39,079 --> 00:07:39,420
That was it.

63
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:40,420
That was the instructions.

64
00:07:40,480 --> 00:07:43,983
None of this was about watch the breath, you know, all I've done for you now.

65
00:07:44,404 --> 00:07:44,824
None of that.

66
00:07:44,845 --> 00:07:47,908
Just sit here and watch whatever comes up, you see.

67
00:07:49,028 --> 00:07:54,494
And by the end of that 40 minutes, I just knew that this was going to get me out of my problems.

68
00:07:54,613 --> 00:08:01,139
I just had that intuitive feeling that this was the path that was going to get me out of my emotional state.

69
00:08:01,728 --> 00:08:04,610
And over a period of time, that's exactly what happened.

70
00:08:05,192 --> 00:08:18,406
I stayed with Zen Buddhism, there's a monastery up in Northumberland, for three years, and then I became involved with the Theravada type of Buddhism, which you find in Southeast Asia, Thailand, Burma, Sri Lanka, those sorts of places.

71
00:08:19,327 --> 00:08:31,482
And it was in that that I met my teacher of this particular tradition that I've taught you, who was a disciple of the Mahasi Saidor, a very famous teacher from Burma.

72
00:08:31,612 --> 00:08:41,309
And shortly after that, after a bit of a struggle, I decided to spend three years in the order to develop meditation.

73
00:08:42,672 --> 00:08:46,238
And it's been 20 years, I've just not been able to get out.

74
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:48,422
So it's just one of those things.

75
00:08:48,982 --> 00:08:50,926
I only joined up for three, and here I am.

76
00:08:52,249 --> 00:08:53,571
So...

77
00:08:55,272 --> 00:09:09,090
The reason for telling you these little things is because one of my struggles, you can say, small s, was, of course, to accommodate what I had learned in Christianity into my Buddhism.

78
00:09:09,610 --> 00:09:15,798
It wasn't a case of me of saying that, you know, that was all the past and it was all rubbish and I didn't want anything to do with it.

79
00:09:16,299 --> 00:09:20,706
It was within my heart there's always been this very...

80
00:09:20,686 --> 00:09:37,902
intimate connection with Jesus Christ because I developed it for the first 15 years of my life for heaven's sake so it wasn't a case of trying to deny that that would have been ridiculous so I had to as it were come to terms and find a

81
00:09:37,881 --> 00:09:48,038
find an explanation, you might say, for the teachings of Christ through this new prism that I'd found in Buddhism, which had worked for me.

82
00:09:48,558 --> 00:09:53,647
And, of course, I reminded myself that in the early days, Christianity had worked for me.

83
00:09:53,667 --> 00:10:00,278
The form that I had had actually given me the basis for all the spirituality that came afterwards.

84
00:10:00,418 --> 00:10:02,421
The basis was, first of all,

85
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:09,735
a moral understanding of life, clear moral understanding of life, and secondly, an understanding that there was an interior life.

86
00:10:11,057 --> 00:10:17,889
I mean, these days, so many people have no idea of what religious emotions are.

87
00:10:18,611 --> 00:10:19,472
No idea whatsoever.

88
00:10:20,094 --> 00:10:22,418
They confuse it with rock and stuff like that.

89
00:10:22,538 --> 00:10:25,725
So,

90
00:10:25,705 --> 00:10:37,799
On that sort of basis, when I came to Buddhism, and I found what Buddhism was doing was to investigate this whole phenomena, which I call myself, this psychophysical organism, you see.

91
00:10:37,919 --> 00:10:47,611
I had to, as it were, meld them together and bring them away from what was a feeling of contradiction to a feeling of complementarity.

92
00:10:47,591 --> 00:10:58,145
And so I've chosen here three or four quotations just to give you an idea of what that has meant for me personally.

93
00:10:58,446 --> 00:11:02,572
This isn't the Buddhist interpretation of the works of Jesus, you understand.

94
00:11:02,591 --> 00:11:08,740
This is a particular person's perspective on his words.

95
00:11:09,107 --> 00:11:17,677
So the first one I'd like to point to is the very rich young man who comes to him and says, I followed the law perfectly.

96
00:11:18,359 --> 00:11:22,243
And he says, what must I do now to enter the kingdom of heaven?

97
00:11:22,263 --> 00:11:28,090
And Jesus' reply is, go sell everything you have and give to the poor and you will have the treasure in heaven.

98
00:11:28,470 --> 00:11:29,871
Then come and follow me.

99
00:11:30,653 --> 00:11:33,436
So this business of go sell everything, right?

100
00:11:33,836 --> 00:11:35,317
In other words, give everything up.

101
00:11:36,058 --> 00:11:38,642
Now, he then goes on

102
00:11:39,448 --> 00:12:00,528
to another place which is in these are two different gospels the first is in Mark second in Luke where he says something which is very hard for us to take which is if anyone comes to me and does not hate their father and mother their wife and children their brothers and sisters yet even their own life they cannot be my disciple that's pretty heavy isn't it

103
00:12:00,509 --> 00:12:09,798
And if you remember there's one point where, I can't remember the details, I'm sure you'll remind me, where he says to his mother, I have no mother.

104
00:12:10,599 --> 00:12:11,620
Yeah, I have no mother.

105
00:12:12,341 --> 00:12:14,722
Now the fact of the matter is that he had a mother.

106
00:12:16,745 --> 00:12:18,186
So what was he saying?

107
00:12:18,206 --> 00:12:20,207
What did he mean by saying I have no mother?

108
00:12:20,749 --> 00:12:26,955
What does he mean by saying those who hate their father and mother, what does he mean by giving up everything, you see?

109
00:12:27,677 --> 00:12:35,849
Now, one of the core teachings of the Buddha is the teaching around detachment and what detachment actually means.

110
00:12:38,032 --> 00:12:49,528
In the meditation here, I asked you to catch how you were relating to what was arising, how everything which you were perceiving as pleasant, you were moving towards and trying to develop it.

111
00:12:50,227 --> 00:12:56,537
Even if you didn't catch it here in your meditation, just consider how you gravitate towards a cup of tea.

112
00:12:56,904 --> 00:12:59,389
And what it feels like when there is no tea.

113
00:13:00,211 --> 00:13:04,240
Can you imagine waking up in the morning and finding there's no tea in the house?

114
00:13:05,162 --> 00:13:07,147
You see, that's pure misery.

115
00:13:09,171 --> 00:13:16,787
So that attachment, that gravitation, that holding on to things, you see, what are we actually doing when we do that?

116
00:13:18,421 --> 00:13:21,946
What are we doing when we say, you know, I have to have my tea?

117
00:13:23,027 --> 00:13:28,153
Clinging on to relationships, my wife, my children, my family.

118
00:13:28,293 --> 00:13:29,294
What are we doing, you see?

119
00:13:29,916 --> 00:13:33,581
In Buddhist understanding, we're seeking happiness right there.

120
00:13:35,984 --> 00:13:37,886
That's what we're doing.

121
00:13:37,907 --> 00:13:46,317
We are investing in something which is phenomenal, something which is arising and passing away, and demanding that it makes us happy.

122
00:13:48,879 --> 00:13:57,451
Now the problem is that when you attach like that, when you demand something like that, that anything in this phenomenal world is going to let you down.

123
00:13:58,052 --> 00:14:02,739
Because the first thing I asked you to notice was that everything is arising and passing away.

124
00:14:03,740 --> 00:14:11,490
So the Buddha's statement on go sell everything you have is, there is nothing in this world worth holding on to.

125
00:14:14,335 --> 00:14:14,414
See?

126
00:14:14,732 --> 00:14:22,895
That's what would be the Buddha's commentary, should we say, on Jesus' go sell everything.

127
00:14:22,916 --> 00:14:30,177
Now, in his lifetime, if you remember, if you know the story, he comes to what I would call an existential crisis.

128
00:14:30,442 --> 00:14:41,961
He gets to the age of 25, middle 20s, when most people come to recognise that youth is over and they'd better start taking life a bit more seriously.

129
00:14:42,621 --> 00:14:46,528
And they get married, get a job, and the pension comes a bit later.

130
00:14:46,508 --> 00:14:55,440
And then, in that seriousness, you see, the Buddha's own experience is put in mythological form.

131
00:14:55,919 --> 00:15:01,106
So he's guarded from the certain realities of life, and he's out hunting on three occasions.

132
00:15:01,768 --> 00:15:11,841
And in each occasion, respectively, he sees somebody who's very sick, like a leper, somebody who is very, very old and crotchety and hardly able to move, and a corpse.

133
00:15:11,821 --> 00:15:13,904
And each time his question is, well, what is this?

134
00:15:14,385 --> 00:15:16,269
And then he's told, well, this is a human being.

135
00:15:16,308 --> 00:15:17,831
This is what happens to people.

136
00:15:18,393 --> 00:15:21,278
And then he says the crucial question, does this happen to me?

137
00:15:22,881 --> 00:15:25,206
So here we have the existential crisis.

138
00:15:25,625 --> 00:15:32,018
And it was with this that he left his wife and his child was just born.

139
00:15:32,519 --> 00:15:36,346
Now some people think that's very, very selfish, but then you know a man's got to do what a man's got to do.

140
00:15:39,032 --> 00:15:42,097
He leaves his child, he cuts his hair off.

141
00:15:42,077 --> 00:15:45,323
He goes to the river with his assistant, Channa.

142
00:15:45,464 --> 00:15:49,392
He goes with his horse, his lovely horse that he loves, and the horse loves him, Tantaka.

143
00:15:49,652 --> 00:16:01,554
He goes to the river, remember the Rubicon, over the river, it's all mythological, cuts his hair off, throws all his robes and finery away, puts on rag robes and crosses the river.

144
00:16:02,657 --> 00:16:04,760
And his horse is so upset he dies of grief.

145
00:16:06,529 --> 00:16:08,693
So then he spends his years training.

146
00:16:08,994 --> 00:16:14,082
So here you see, one who comes to me and does not hate their mother, hate their father, wife.

147
00:16:15,085 --> 00:16:24,360
If you define the word hate as some sort of negativity towards these people, then obviously I think you've misunderstood here the teachings of Christ.

148
00:16:24,621 --> 00:16:31,474
And I've read somewhere that this is a very strong Jewish way of saying to be detached.

149
00:16:31,690 --> 00:16:32,571
to be detached.

150
00:16:33,211 --> 00:16:36,936
In other words, not to find happiness in that other person.

151
00:16:37,996 --> 00:16:53,253
Now, this whole process of letting go, if you get into Buddhist circles, you come across these little pat phrases like letting go, let it go, let it pass, don't own it.

152
00:16:53,994 --> 00:17:01,241
Now, when you are in yourself in the way that you were instructed a minute ago,

153
00:17:01,475 --> 00:17:02,355
You were detached.

154
00:17:03,197 --> 00:17:05,300
That's what the Buddhist understanding is.

155
00:17:05,981 --> 00:17:10,167
Most times, when you feel depression, when you feel depressed, what do you say to yourself?

156
00:17:10,208 --> 00:17:11,349
You say, I am depressed.

157
00:17:11,930 --> 00:17:12,912
So how are you going to get out of that?

158
00:17:14,134 --> 00:17:14,894
I am depressed.

159
00:17:15,015 --> 00:17:15,355
That's it.

160
00:17:15,715 --> 00:17:17,959
So all you can do now is get depressed about being depressed.

161
00:17:19,101 --> 00:17:25,170
And then you get angry about being depressed, and you get very afraid of being depressed, and it goes down into a spiral, and you end up in Prozac.

162
00:17:26,752 --> 00:17:42,094
Now, if you were to sit inside yourself as I instructed, there, and you notice that there is depression, not I am depressed, there, you see, then of course you don't have the reaction of being depressed about being depressed.

163
00:17:42,554 --> 00:17:46,720
And you've discovered a place within yourself which cannot be touched by depression.

164
00:17:48,656 --> 00:17:55,304
When you have pain, should we say, the sitting posture there, you might have got some pain discomfort, or you've got a headache sometimes.

165
00:17:55,585 --> 00:18:01,751
Instead of saying, I have a headache, owning the headache, so you immediately form a relationship of attachment.

166
00:18:02,491 --> 00:18:08,098
If you sit there quietly and feel the sensations of your headache, there's the headache, there.

167
00:18:10,480 --> 00:18:17,449
And that which actually is experiencing that headache comes to understand that it itself does not have a headache.

168
00:18:19,926 --> 00:18:41,601
Now these are very deep insights because there is something in us which is experiencing directly everything that we call ourselves to be a human being, which is our sensations, which is our actions, which is our feelings and emotions, which is our thought and which is our images, and yet which isn't that.

169
00:18:43,163 --> 00:18:43,825
So what is it?

170
00:18:46,066 --> 00:19:04,327
Now, if that within us is not the body, if that within us is not the heart with its emotional states, if it's not thought, you see, then it hates, it is detached from the very psychophysical phenomena that we call a human being.

171
00:19:07,210 --> 00:19:18,317
Now that detachment, you see, is then confused with being some sort of callous, unregarding, unlovable way of being.

172
00:19:18,904 --> 00:19:43,748
But then, when you discover that position of yourself of being with your body, heart and mind, you begin to realize that you can now use it, as it were, or you can have a relationship with it, which is kind, which is generous, which is compassionate, and yet, somehow, because you're detached, you're no longer upset by what it's actually doing.

173
00:19:44,707 --> 00:19:56,863
So if this body is something that this within us is in, we would call it something like the Buddha nature, when the body gets sick, there's a compassionate movement towards the body.

174
00:19:57,544 --> 00:19:58,365
Why fear it?

175
00:19:59,086 --> 00:20:01,529
Why should you fear the sickness of the body when it's not you?

176
00:20:04,513 --> 00:20:09,279
And when an emotion comes, why should you be so concerned about it when it's not you?

177
00:20:09,984 --> 00:20:15,111
So somehow this detaching is a process of liberating ourselves.

178
00:20:15,671 --> 00:20:21,397
And that's exactly what the Buddha means by detaching, and that's exactly what we mean by nibbana.

179
00:20:21,857 --> 00:20:24,740
Nibbana translates as unshackling.

180
00:20:25,162 --> 00:20:26,884
What is it that's being unshackled?

181
00:20:27,284 --> 00:20:29,547
What is it that's being liberated, you see?

182
00:20:30,007 --> 00:20:33,411
It's that within us which knows, which experiences.

183
00:20:35,955 --> 00:20:44,255
And once we can develop this sort of attitude towards ourselves, we develop the same attitude towards others.

184
00:20:45,238 --> 00:20:50,589
So at the end of this particular period, I'll do a loving kindness meditation.

185
00:20:51,143 --> 00:20:58,854
And the loving-kindness meditation, or the meditation of goodwill, is taking what we feel about somebody for whom we like.

186
00:20:59,094 --> 00:21:00,636
See, it's easy to love somebody you like.

187
00:21:01,857 --> 00:21:11,531
So you take somebody whom you like, whom you have a warm relationship with anyway, and then you keep displacing that image with people...

188
00:21:11,832 --> 00:21:22,669
whom you hardly know, to all beings, so that this love that we are developing is not dependent on the object that's standing before us.

189
00:21:23,797 --> 00:21:42,865
So whoever is before me, if I was doing this practice properly, whether it be somebody whom I know intimately, somebody belonging to my own family, for instance, or somebody whom I've never met in my life before, or somebody who stinks, or somebody who hates me, I still have that attitude towards them.

190
00:21:43,705 --> 00:21:50,817
That attitude of love, compassion, sympathetic joy is what we mean by detached joy.

191
00:21:50,932 --> 00:21:53,094
Because it's not attached to the object.

192
00:21:53,594 --> 00:22:06,246
It's an attitude which we have within our own hearts, which is developed within our own hearts, not dependent on the object.

193
00:22:06,266 --> 00:22:12,231
Now, to get to that level, you've got to go and sell everything and hate your mother and father.

194
00:22:12,711 --> 00:22:16,215
So now, do you have to do that, you see?

195
00:22:16,236 --> 00:22:18,778
I mean, if you take these words literally, you see,

196
00:22:19,535 --> 00:22:24,021
If you take the words literally, then you're really going to have to sell everything.

197
00:22:25,202 --> 00:22:27,926
And if you take the words hate, then you're really going to have to hate.

198
00:22:28,008 --> 00:22:29,028
But it's not that at all.

199
00:22:29,609 --> 00:22:38,182
What Jesus, in the Buddhist point of view, is pointing to here is forming a completely different relationship to those things that you own.

200
00:22:38,222 --> 00:22:43,230
And a completely different relationship to those people who you relate to.

201
00:22:44,948 --> 00:22:59,391
And the underlying movement in the psychology, the underlying movement in, shall we say, rather than psychology, the philosophy behind it all, is that whatever happiness is, you're not going to find it in the sensual world.

202
00:22:59,971 --> 00:23:01,894
And you're not going to find it in somebody else.

203
00:23:04,019 --> 00:23:06,001
Other people can't make you happy.

204
00:23:08,125 --> 00:23:12,271
When you grasp that, then you'll stop demanding that they do so.

205
00:23:12,386 --> 00:23:19,998
and it feels very liberating on those people around you, I can tell you.

206
00:23:20,018 --> 00:23:24,023
So, leaving that, I now want to get a little bit more mystical.

207
00:23:25,526 --> 00:23:35,580
And, well, no, the third quote was, my commandment is this, to love each other as I have loved you.

208
00:23:35,641 --> 00:23:41,449
Now, that is in stark contrast to hate your mother, hate your father.

209
00:23:41,782 --> 00:23:50,991
You're not going to understand this love business unless you understand clearly this other statement about hating your mother and father.

210
00:23:51,172 --> 00:23:53,314
That's what I was pointing to there.

211
00:23:53,334 --> 00:23:55,256
So those two statements go together.

212
00:23:55,715 --> 00:24:05,405
If anyone comes to me and does not hate their father, their mother, their wife, their children, their brothers and sisters, yet even their own life, they cannot be my disciple.

213
00:24:05,925 --> 00:24:08,989
But my commandment to you is this, to love one another as I love you.

214
00:24:10,166 --> 00:24:16,022
If you can get beyond that paradox, then you've understood the true message of the spiritual life.

215
00:24:16,303 --> 00:24:22,539
And you'll find that in every religion through its mystics.

216
00:24:24,021 --> 00:24:26,326
Now I want to get a bit more mystical.

217
00:24:26,766 --> 00:24:30,711
So there's this commandment.

218
00:24:30,732 --> 00:24:33,356
Well, Jesus says, I am the father of one.

219
00:24:34,097 --> 00:24:36,981
I am in my father and you are in me and I am in you.

220
00:24:37,702 --> 00:24:43,853
Now, this was the real struggle that I had, you see.

221
00:24:45,148 --> 00:24:54,123
Remember that in Catholicism, the host at Mass is changed into the veritable body of Jesus Christ.

222
00:24:54,143 --> 00:24:59,010
So the bread is the body, even though it's under the species of bread.

223
00:24:59,171 --> 00:25:02,195
It tastes like bread and everything, but actually it is the body.

224
00:25:02,175 --> 00:25:04,000
And the wine is actually the blood.

225
00:25:04,059 --> 00:25:09,691
Even though it tastes like wine, it is actually the blood.

226
00:25:10,172 --> 00:25:16,624
And this, of course, is the separation of substance from attributes.

227
00:25:17,093 --> 00:25:21,778
Now, that really just didn't make sense to me.

228
00:25:22,558 --> 00:25:45,665
If I wanted to give you a critique of that from, shall we say, one of the greatest philosophers of the human race, Nagarjuna, who, in a sense, brought philosophy to an end when we're talking about metaphysical philosophy, he simply states, if the substance of a thing is different from the attributes...

229
00:25:46,237 --> 00:25:47,258
how do you know it exists?

230
00:25:48,200 --> 00:25:51,444
Because the only way you know something exists is from its attributes.

231
00:25:51,464 --> 00:25:55,309
Whether it's hard or soft, or whether you can see it's yellow or blue.

232
00:25:56,592 --> 00:26:01,819
And then he says, if the substance and the attributes are the same, why make a difference?

233
00:26:03,682 --> 00:26:12,496
So, this problem around substance and attributes is a philosophical problem, you might say.

234
00:26:13,497 --> 00:26:14,218
Now,

235
00:26:15,176 --> 00:26:23,057
Jesus says, and of course correct me if I'm wrong here, unless you eat my body and drink my blood, you cannot, I think, enter the kingdom of heaven?

236
00:26:23,178 --> 00:26:23,859
Something like that, yeah?

237
00:26:24,260 --> 00:26:24,883
Something like that, yeah?

238
00:26:25,103 --> 00:26:28,511
But it's eat my body, and of course people were disgusted and they all walked away.

239
00:26:29,385 --> 00:26:47,174
Then just before his passion, he instigates this ritual, which is, to my mind, the loveliest of rituals that you'll come across in any religion, which is the sharing of the bread and the wine.

240
00:26:47,976 --> 00:26:55,788
And he says of the bread, this is my body, take of this, etc., etc., this is the wine, the blood I shed for the new covenant.

241
00:26:55,868 --> 00:26:56,710
Okay.

242
00:26:56,942 --> 00:27:06,951
So he's equated body and flesh, flesh and blood rather, with the bread and the wine, right?

243
00:27:06,971 --> 00:27:10,494
And he's always referring to himself.

244
00:27:11,076 --> 00:27:22,165
Now, I long struggled with this, and it was only because I visited a friend of mine who was an elderly Sri Lankan man, and I must tell you, in truth, I went there for toast.

245
00:27:23,027 --> 00:27:26,730
But I also went there for... You can't get toast, I'm sorry.

246
00:27:28,516 --> 00:27:36,208
While I was eating my toast, I was able to have long conversations with him about this business.

247
00:27:36,628 --> 00:27:41,195
And for him it was not a problem, because he was brought up a Catholic and then became a Hindu.

248
00:27:42,198 --> 00:27:52,734
And he also accepted all the stuff that Catholicism had taught him in that mystical way, in the way of metaphor, you see, the way of metaphor.

249
00:27:52,714 --> 00:27:56,921
And it was funny how long it took for me for the penny to drop.

250
00:27:57,622 --> 00:28:09,519
And it was the way of looking, it was the way of thinking that every time Jesus Christ talked about himself, he was actually talking about the phenomena that we call Jesus.

251
00:28:09,859 --> 00:28:12,964
Meaning the body, heart and mind that you've just been looking at.

252
00:28:14,346 --> 00:28:15,990
And that was where my confusion lay.

253
00:28:16,029 --> 00:28:21,017
And that was coming to me through a little bit, I have to say, my Catholic upbringing.

254
00:28:21,875 --> 00:28:28,846
It was only when I realized that when he talked about flesh and blood, when he talked about bread and wine, he wasn't talking about that at all.

255
00:28:28,946 --> 00:28:31,711
What he was talking about was the Christ within him.

256
00:28:32,752 --> 00:28:37,421
I am the Father of one, and I am in the Father, you are in me, I am in you.

257
00:28:37,500 --> 00:28:41,367
I mean, you can't get more deep than saying I am in you and you are in me.

258
00:28:41,347 --> 00:28:55,247
So now, what is it that is the bread and what is it that is the wine within that nature that he's pointing to, which is that which is in me, in you, me and the Father one, etc., etc.

259
00:28:56,387 --> 00:29:01,634
And when you meditate, when you begin to do this form of meditation I've taught you,

260
00:29:01,935 --> 00:29:11,454
you will begin to abstract, you'll begin to disembed from the mass that you call yourself, this peculiar quality of intuitive intelligence.

261
00:29:12,257 --> 00:29:14,882
And it begins with an awareness.

262
00:29:15,030 --> 00:29:15,892
It begins now.

263
00:29:16,112 --> 00:29:18,275
It's not as though awareness is not always with you.

264
00:29:18,414 --> 00:29:20,636
It's not as though consciousness is not always with you.

265
00:29:20,656 --> 00:29:21,478
It's always there.

266
00:29:21,538 --> 00:29:22,759
It's even there when you're asleep.

267
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:24,040
Somebody turns you over.

268
00:29:25,162 --> 00:29:27,044
Somebody pulls a blanket over you when you feel cold.

269
00:29:27,805 --> 00:29:28,746
And somebody wakes up.

270
00:29:29,185 --> 00:29:33,009
Somebody hears the bell, the alarm clock, and then there you are.

271
00:29:34,011 --> 00:29:36,673
Normally we associate awareness with just, here I am.

272
00:29:37,875 --> 00:29:39,958
I mean, you go to sleep, and where are you?

